# Next.js Enterprise Best Practices

## Layout & shadcn Design Tokens

Avoid hardcoded layout values. Use design tokens from `globals.css` and `@/lib/layout-tokens`:

- **Page min-height** (error/not-found): `page-min-h` or `layoutTokens.pageMinH`
- **Auth form width**: `auth-max-w` â€” use instead of `max-w-[400px]`
- **Table columns**: `col-account`, `col-amount`, `col-actions`, `col-key`, `col-date`
- **Truncate text**: `truncate-layout-sm`, `truncate-layout-md` (with `truncate`)
- **Select widths**: `select-width-sm`, `select-width-md`, `select-width-lg`
- **Skeletons**: `skeleton-row`, `skeleton-table`, `skeleton-chart`

All tokens are CSS variables (`--layout-*`, `--shadow-card-hover`) in `globals.css` â€” change once, apply everywhere.

## Next.js MCP (next-devtools)

When working on `apps/web`, call the `init` tool from next-devtools-mcp at session start to establish context and documentation requirements. The dev server must be running (`pnpm dev` or `pnpm --filter @afenda/web dev`) for runtime tools (get_errors, get_page_metadata, get_logs) to work.

Apply these patterns when building or refactoring the Afenda web app (`apps/web`).

## App Router Patterns

### 1. Async params and searchParams (Next.js 15+)

Always type `params` and `searchParams` as `Promise<>` and await them:

```tsx
// âś“ Correct
export default async function Page({
  params,
  searchParams,
}: {
  params: Promise<{ id: string }>;
  searchParams: Promise<{ page?: string; status?: string }>;
}) {
  const { id } = await params;
  const sp = await searchParams;
  // ...
}
```

### 2. Streaming with Suspense

Avoid data waterfalls. Use Suspense boundaries for independent data sections:

```tsx
// âś“ Good: Streams each section independently
export default function DashboardPage() {
  return (
    <div>
      <PageHeader />
      <ModuleDashboard scope={...} />
      <Suspense fallback={<SummarySkeleton />}>
        <AsyncSummarySection />
      </Suspense>
    </div>
  );
}

async function AsyncSummarySection() {
  const data = await getSummary();
  return <SummaryCards data={data} />;
}
```

### 3. Parallel fetches with Promise.all

When multiple fetches don't depend on each other, run them in parallel:

```tsx
// âś“ Good
const [users, stats, activity] = await Promise.all([
  getUsers(),
  getStats(),
  getRecentActivity(),
]);
```

### 4. Metadata export

Every `page.tsx` under `(shell)/` should export `metadata` or `generateMetadata`:

- **Static routes**: Use `metadata` object.
- **Dynamic routes** (`[id]`, `[slug]`): Use `generateMetadata` for per-entity SEO.

```tsx
import type { Metadata } from 'next';

// Static
export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: 'Page Title | Module',
  description: 'Brief description for SEO.',
  openGraph: { title: 'Page Title | Afenda', description: '...' },
};

// Dynamic â€” fetch entity, return title/description from data
export async function generateMetadata({ params }: { params: Promise<{ id: string }> }): Promise<Metadata> {
  const { id } = await params;
  const entity = await getEntity(id);
  if (!entity) return { title: 'Entity | Module' };
  return {
    title: `${entity.name} | Module | Finance`,
    description: `Entity ${entity.name} â€” ${entity.status}`,
  };
}
```

## Data Flow

- **Reads**: Server Components fetch directly via typed API client; no client-side fetch for initial data.
- **Writes**: Server Actions with `'use server'`; validate with Zod schemas from `@afenda/contracts`.
- **Client state**: Minimize `'use client'`; use only for forms, toggles, dropdowns, and browser APIs.

## Images

- Use `next/image` for all images with `https://` URLs.
- Fallback to `<img>` only for `blob:` or `data:` URLs (e.g. client-side preview before upload).
- Ensure external domains are in `next.config.ts` `images.remotePatterns`.

## Loading and Errors

- Provide `loading.tsx` per route segment for instant navigation feedback.
- Provide `error.tsx` per route segment for graceful degradation.
- Use `Suspense` fallbacks that match the final content shape (skeletons, not spinners).

## File Conventions

- `page.tsx` â€” thin, composes blocks and passes data.
- `loading.tsx` â€” sibling to `page.tsx` for route-level loading.
- `error.tsx` â€” sibling to `page.tsx` for error boundaries.
- `not-found.tsx` â€” 404 UI where applicable.
